[normal]&#xa0;[bold]Case A -  [bold]Family Y [bold]v Home Office [bold]A family with
[normal] two young children
[normal] were detained
[normal] for
[normal] 
[normal]two
[normal] 
[normal]periods
[normal] 
[normal]at
[normal] 
[normal]Yarl’s
[normal] 
[normal]Wood IRC in April 2009 for 
[normal]11
[normal] 
[normal]days
[normal] 
[normal]and September 2009 for 15
[normal] 
[normal]days. The adults are 
[normal]foreign 
[normal]nationals who met in the 
[normal]UK
[normal].
[normal] 
[normal]The
[normal]y
[normal] were 
[normal]seeking leave to remain on the basis of Article 8 and/or the Imm
[normal]igration Rules and 
[normal]would not, therefore, qualify under any exception to the residence test.  
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]On t
[normal]wo separate occasions the parent
[normal]s
[normal]’
[normal] immigration applications were refused unbeknown to them and certified, thereby precluding any in country right of appeal.
[normal] On both occasions, without notice and in breach of policy, dawn raids were conducted on the family home. They were told to pack their
[normal] belongings for removal and taken with their children in a caged prison-like van to for detention in 
[normal]Yarl’s
[normal] Wood Immigration Reception Centre. The children vomited in the van. The second enforcement action took place despite compliance with release conditi
[normal]ons.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]Removal
[normal] 
[normal]was halted by a judicial review, which was ulti
[normal]mately settled by consent with the
[normal] 
[normal]grant of 
[normal]an in country right of appeal. 
[normal]T
[normal]he family 
[normal]was finally released following an 
[normal]opposed application for bail
[normal].
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]A claim was brought for
[normal] false imprisonment 
[normal]as well as b
[normal]reaches of human 
[normal]rights including Articles 3, 5 and 8
[normal] ECHR
[normal]. 
[normal]It settled with
[normal] 
[normal]significant sum
[normal]s
[normal] 
[normal]for all Claimants for both detentions. 
