[normal]&#xa0;[bold]&#xa0;[bold]C[bold]ivil remedies[bold] for breaches[bold] within the criminal justice system[bold]&#xa0;[bold]&#xa0;[bold]Case D - [bold]Female prisoner suffering sexual harassment by male prison staff[bold]&#xa0;[bold]JS was a Thai woman who was
[normal] detained at HMP Holloway for two and a half years pending extradition to the 
[normal]US
[normal] after being stopped in transit at a 
[normal]UK
[normal] airport.
[normal] 
[normal]She
[normal] would fall foul of the residence test, having no leave to be in the 
[normal]UK
[normal] at any time. 
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]JS suffered on-going sexual 
[normal]harassment over many months by two male members of staff. The men exposed themselves
[normal] to her and demanded oral sex, 
[normal]ordered her to undress in her cell and grabbed at her genitals when she came out of the showers. She was also subject to repeated obscene ver
[normal]bal sexual harassment during this period on frequent occasions.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]When JS finally reported the events
[normal] internal prison investigations found no case to answer in respect of one officer.
[normal] The second member of staff faced an internal disciplinary hearing over a 
[normal]year later. The allegat
[normal]ions of JS were found unproven and 
[normal]JS was not informed of the outcome of the hearing for five months.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]JS issued proceedings for b
[normal]reaches of the Human Rights Act (articles 3 and 8 ECHR),
[normal] breaches of the investigative duty on the part
[normal] of the prison in the way in which her complaints were handled. 
[normal]S
[normal]he
[normal] also
[normal] claimed sex discrimination under article 14 ECHR and under the Sex Discrimination Act 1975 as well as race discrimination due to her treatment being the result of stereotyping of her 
[normal]as a Thai woman being a prostitute/ promiscuous. 
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]A settlement of the civil claim was reached at £30,000
[normal] 
[normal]which included 
[normal]a series of steps to be taken by the prison as 
[normal]a result of the lessons learnt, requiring 
[normal]the prison authorities to re-examine the way i
[normal]n which very serious misconduct had been handled.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]Case E - [bold]Foreign national mother in prison[bold]&#xa0;
[normal]BB was a foreign national who gave birth to a baby with disabilities while on remand.  She spoke no English. After her sentence she was informed that the baby would be removed as they did not know if she would be allowed to remain with her baby when she 
[normal]wa
[normal]s eventually returned to 
[normal]Spain
[normal].  After taking legal advice it was possible to establish that the Spanish authorities would accept her home to serve her sentence and would allow her to remain with her baby.  The decision was reversed.  Aside from the human 
[normal]costs of an unnecessary separation of mother and child, the cost to the public purse would have been enormous.
[normal] BB would have fallen foul of the residence test because, although an EU citizen, she was not present in the 
[normal]UK
[normal] 
[normal]as a result of 
[normal]exercising EU right
[normal]s and had no other 
[normal]right of residence.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]Case F - [bold]Unlawful arrest and police caution[bold]KA is a 29 year old man from 
[normal]Bangladesh
[normal] with no previous convictions, cautions or arrests
[normal]. 
[normal]KA had been living in the 
[normal]UK
[normal] on a spouse visa for less than 12 months
[normal]. His relationship broke down leaving him without leave in the 
[normal]UK
[normal] and
[normal] he
[normal] would therefore have fallen foul of the residence test.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]KA suffered an assault and attended a police station to report this. Instead of his allegation being dealt with KA was arreste
[normal]d on the basis that his assailant had attended the station a few hours previously and made an allegation of assault against him. 
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]KA consistently denied committing an assault. Officers told him that if he admitted it he could go home but if he did not he 
[normal]would have to stay in custody for two to three months. KA signed a document which he later discovered had been a consent to a police caution.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]KA successfully challenged the lawfulness of the caution by way of judicial review proceedings. As a result of hi
[normal]s complaint the officers were disciplined and issued
[normal] 
[normal]with
[normal] 
[normal]written
[normal] 
[normal]warnings for unprofessional 
[normal]behaviour
[normal]. 
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]The police communicated incorrect information about the caution to the 
[normal]UK
[normal] Border Agency, seriously 
[normal]jeopardising
[normal] KA’s application for indefinite leave
[normal] to remain. Upon KA’s challenge the information was rectified.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]The claim settled for £20,000 plus an apology. KA was subsequently granted indefinite leave to remain. 
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]Case G - [bold]Death in custody [bold]WW was a 32-year old man from the 
[normal]Republic
[normal] of 
[normal]Ireland
[normal]. He ha
[normal]d a history of drug, alcohol and mental health problems, including self harming. WW was arrested in 
[normal]London
[normal] and remanded in custody pending extradition to the 
[normal]Republic
[normal] of 
[normal]Ireland
[normal].
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]On arrival at HMP Brixton, WW was displaying signs of alcohol / drug withdra
[normal]wal and referred by a doctor for a mental health assessment which never took place. During five weeks’ detention WW was never seen by a member of the mental health outreach team, despite two referrals being made, nor by the substance misuse team. When he r
[normal]eported that he would rather be extradited dead than alive he was made subject to self harm procedures which were withdrawn within 24 hours and he was found hanging the following morning.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]An inquest jury found that WW hanged himself whilst the balance of 
[normal]his mind was disturbed and that his death was contributed to by neglect.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]WW’s family were citizens of the 
[normal]Republic
[normal] of 
[normal]Ireland
[normal] and therefore not lawfully resident in the 
[normal]UK
[normal]. A claim was brought under the Human Rights Act for breach of article 2 ECHR, the 
[normal]right to life, which was settled for £15,000.
