[normal]Case H - [bold]Unrecognised[bold] trafficking victim[bold]AS
[normal] [bold]is
[normal] 
[normal]a
[normal] 
[normal]19
[normal] 
[normal]year-old
[normal] 
[normal]Nigerian
[normal] 
[normal]national
[normal] 
[normal]and
[normal] 
[normal]a
[normal] 
[normal]vic
[normal]tim
[normal] 
[normal]of
[normal] 
[normal]trafficking,
[normal] 
[normal]forced
[normal] 
[normal]labour
[normal] 
[normal]and physical
[normal] 
[normal]abuse
[normal] 
[normal]at
[normal] 
[normal]the
[normal] 
[normal]hands
[normal] 
[normal]of
[normal] 
[normal]her
[normal] 
[normal]aunt,
[normal] 
[normal]her
[normal] 
[normal]aunt’s
[normal] 
[normal]husband
[normal] 
[normal]and
[normal] 
[normal]her
[normal] 
[normal]maternal
[normal] 
[normal]grandmother. AS’s aunt brought her to the 
[normal]UK
[normal] in 2007 where she subjected her to sustained physical abuse. In 2009 AS reported the abuse
[normal] 
[normal]to
[normal] 
[normal]her
[normal] 
[normal]teachers
[normal] 
[normal]and local Social
[normal] 
[normal]Services who sent a social worker to speak to AS but took no further steps to investigate the abuse. In 2012 AS reported the abuse 
[normal]to the police who closed the investigation a week later. AS claims violation of her rights pursuant to Articles 3 and 4 ECHR, on the basis that the police and social services have failed to protect her from inhuman and degrading treatment and from being he
[normal]ld in servitude.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]In September 2012 the Home Office decided that there were reasonable grounds to believe that AS was a victim of trafficking. She then began a claim for asylum. She has a strong connection with the 
[normal]UK
[normal] by virtue of being a victim of abuse i
[normal]n the 
[normal]UK
[normal] over a five-year period. Nevertheless AS would appear to fall foul of the residence test because the reasonable grounds decision was not made until after the commencement of her civil claim and her claim for asylum was brought after that decision.
[normal] Had the civil claim been postponed until after the decision the limitation period under the Human Rights Act would have expired.
